aity,” and no records were made. From it came the election of Samuel Seabury, first Bishop of the Church in America."},{"number":2,"category":"character","header":"A sliding panel hid the rector","body":"Twice beaten in the road and left for dead, Marshall could finally leave his house only on Sundays, when the old Puritan law forbade arrest on the Sabbath. The Committee of Patriots searched the glebe again and again — never finding the sliding closet panel that dropped him into the cellar."},{"number":3,"category":"religion","header":"He furnished the glass and nails","body":"When the Society withdrew its aid at the war’s outbreak, Marshall labored on from Milford to Great Barrington, and when St. Paul’s finally raised its church in 1785 he supplied the glass and nails himself. The Prayer Book he marked up in his own hand anticipated the revised American text he did not live to see adopted."}],"notable":{"is_notable":true,"primary_url":"https://litchfieldmagazine.com/onourradar/glebehouse/","primary_url_label":"Litchfield Magazine","notable_blurb":"Glebe House rector; American Episcopacy organized there","notable_category":["religion","history"]},"slug":"rev-john-rutgers-marshall-x03288"},"HD6318":{"id":"HD6318","bio":{"display_name":"Susannah Anna Maria Marshall Ives","gender":"female"},"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":7,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"has_descendants_documented":false,"number_of_marriages":1,"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1767,"month":2,"day":19,"city":"Stratford","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1849,"month":8,"day":24},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"X03289","date_year":1789,"date_month":1,"date_day":25,"children_ids":[]}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM853"},"parents":{"father_id":"X03288","mother_id":"HD6316"},"slug":"susannah-anna-maria-marshall-ives-hd631